@E0645: print: "panic stop"
@N0040:  call the init subroutine
@N0041:  branch to main display refresh loop
@N0053:  copy preset switches into FF Regs
@N0054:  figure out what message to print
@N0055:  mask to three bits
@N0057:  this is the address into the message table
@N0061:  fetch the message pointer from the table
@N0062:  store a pointer to the start of the string to print.
@N0063:  initialize the length of the string to zero
@N0067:  start the string near the top left edge of the screen
@N0072:  character origin is the lower-left corner, so make sure it doesn't overflow Y axis
@N0075:  this routine prints the string until either a negative character terminator OR the count is exhausted
@N0076:  on each pass, make the string longer by two, up to the max length
@N0105:  used only in top-level routines for drawing the game board
@N0111:  we lengthen the string by one char until it reaches the end and we've counted to msg_maxlen
@N0112:  this should be an offset into the table of messages to select just one
@N0167:  remember that the converted string will count shift-up/down as characters
@N0620:  Constants
@N0630:  loop counter for 12 iterations
@N0632:  constants
@N0634:  close to the edge of the scope screen
@N0636:  +32 in the top half of the word
@N0637:  +32 in the bottom half of the word
@N0644:  ---------------------------------------
@N0651:  remember that the converted string will count shift-up/down as characters
@N0712:        the count is exhausted or a negative character is encountered)
@N0713:  save the character pointer passed in the ACC
@N0720:  walk the string from start to finish
@N0722:  fetch the next character in the string
@N0723:  actually draw the character!
@N0724:  prepare for next char in loop
@N0726:  bail out if the next char is negative, or if the loop count is exhausted
@N0727:  test for a negative number as the marker for the string end; branch out if done
@N0730:  ; decrement the length count
@N0734:  I moved the x and y auto-increment into the character-drawing routine draw_16seg_char
@N0736:  pointer to the next character to display
@N0742:  character value for Carriage Return
@N0743:  character value for Shift Upper
@N0744:  character value for Shift Lower
@N0745:  local storage for the character to be displayed
@N0747:  save the incoming character to be printed
@N0750:  test to see if we've got a "Shift Upper" character
@N0752:  negative zero if acc == c_upper
@N0753:  adjust the current Case, then exit
@N0757:  negative zero if acc == c_lower
@N0760:  adjust the current Case, then exit
@N0764:  negative zero if acc == c_newline
@N0765:  execute a newline, then exit
@N0766:  re-fetch the input character
@N0767:  add the table start addr to the offset in ACC
@N0770:         .print "draw_16seg_char:  char=%ao. d16c_argx=%o, d16c_argy=%o", d16c_argx, d16c_argy
@N0771:  fetch the bit map
@N0773:  prep for 16 times around the loop
@N0775:  walk the segment table back to front
@N0776:  first table entry
@N0777:         td tmp_tabx
@N1000:  second table entry
@N1001:         td tmp_taby
@N1002:  third table entry
@N1003:  end of debug hack
@N1004:  branch if most significant bit is on
@N1006:  shift AC left by one bit
@N1013:         td tmp_tabx
@N1016:         td tmp_taby
@N1023:  advance x position to the next character
@N1026:  bail out when count exhausted
@N1027:  the SI uses the AC to set Y coord
@N1031:  initialize vector gen with the y-coord in ACC
@N1032:  the RC uses AC to set X coord and mem address for the vector length
@N1037:  shift pointer to Upper Case table & exit
@N1042:  shift pointer to Lower Case table & exit
@N1052: ; Return from draw_16seg_char
@N1057:  flexowriter defaults to lower case
